<br>
I'd recommend staying off the flightline, unless you don't mind losing your hearing.  3COX1 (Computer Operator) is a kick ass specialty with a nice bonus attached.  Good skills to have as a backup, lotta choices for duty assignment.<br>
<br>
Also, tell your recruiter about the &quot;altercation&quot; ... Not a big deal, unless you DON'T tell anyone and they find out ... and they will find out eventually when setting up a clearance.<br>
<br>
All the services will help you with your college ...<br>
<br>
I work in a CINC, so I've been around all the services.<br>
<br>
As far as quality of life (read: cushiness), Air Force is your best bet, and overall, we probably have the most number of technical specialties, although you'll find them in each branch.  I think the Air Force has the least culture shock of joining a military environment after leading a civilian career.<br>
<br>
Navy's probably the best for travel, if you can handle sea duty.  Great technical fields.  Would be my second choice.  Except for the boomers.  they give me the willies.<br>
<br>
From a college standpoint, the Army has the best thing going.  If you're in it purely for college, I say go Army.  They have a program that'll pay for the schooling you received before you joined.  The Air Force didn't do that for me, and I'm still paying off my college loans.  (I still love the Air Force, anyway).  If you like the outdoors, you'll LOVE the field, heh ... or you could just try to get into an AF mobility unit ... Plus, the Army's got alot of Hummers!  Mmm, Humvees ...<br>
<br>
If you were going to join the Marines, you'd have known it by now.  It's an attitude, a personality/character kind of thing.  If you're gung ho, go for it.  If you don't jump in whole heartedly, though, get ready for hell.  The Marines, without a doubt, have some of the strongest comraderie between service members that I have seen.<br>
<br>
Oh, and don't forget about the Coasties ... The Coast Guard has a lot of unique job experiences, if you're the nautical type.<br>
<br>
That's all I got for j00... hope some of the other EQ'ers from services other than the AF chime in, too.  They can give you a much better view of their branches than I can, looking from the outside.<br>
<br>
Laters,<br>
