More than just the seventh letter of the alphabet!</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ukidin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kidin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 35<br> <font color=#E9D756>(1/28/02 9:53:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrreallife.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=269.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Military accession indecision...</span><hr size=1> First,<br>
Discount much of what non-active duty or veterans have said.<br>
They haven't been there or done that.<br>
<br>
I am an active duty Navy Sonar Technicians Submarines Petty Officer First Class.  (An STS1/SS, paygrade E-6)  I made it to this rank in 9 years.  I will have 11 years of active service this February, plus an additional year and a half in the Navy Reserves.<br>
<br>
My father retired from the Air Force after 20 years of service as a Lt. Colonel.  (Paygrade O-5)  As an Air Force brat who later became a sailor, I believe I can speak with a little authority about both of these branches.  What I didn't recognize as a child, I can recall now with greater understanding.<br>
<br>
I have served onboard 2 fast attack submarines and one ballistic missile submarine.  Sea duty has been some of the most exciting/boring/best/worst times in my life so far.  I have scrubbed thousands of toilets.  I have led my division (15 men) during times of crisis and in recreation.  I missed my second child's birth.  I have been to 16 foreign countries, places that I would have never been able to visit on my own.<br>
There is no way words written here can accurately describe the military experience.<br>
<br>
You should listen to what the vets have said.  I would NOT listen to anyone who got kicked out or left their branch of service with anything other than an Honorable (not a General, a big difference) Discharge.  Their opinions will obviously be strongly biased in a much different direction than my own, and usually make little attempt at giving an objective view.<br>
<br>
Get it in writing.  Make sure you know what &quot;job&quot; you will be getting.  Do not enlist without a guarantee of some kind of technical schooling.  (In the navy this is called a guaranteed &quot;A&quot; school.  PUSH to get a guarantee of a &quot;C&quot; shcool as well.)   Information Technology and Computer Systems are a hot commodity in the military right now, and the field is here to stay.  If you are computer savvy, this may be a good area to look into in the military.  Free training, with an excellent opportunity for successful transition back to civilian life if the military life doesn't suit you.  <br>
<br>
There are some very good promotion opportunities within the Navy.  Air Force enlisted promotions are generally slower than that found in the Navy, though it is very rating specific.<br>
<br>
Army paygrades are based on a billet structure that I am not very familiar with, but my understanding is you can find yourself getting demoted through no fault of your own if there aren't enough positions within a certain paygrade range when it comes time for you to transfer.<br>
<br>
Marine Corps is a different life entirely.  Strict discipline and regimen, but they enjoy a esprit d' corps that no other branch has.  Promotion there can vary, but their performance evaluation system is the best in my opinion.  You also need to be extremely dedicated to physical fitness.<br>
<br>
<br>
Do not hide anything from the recruiters.  If you choose a rating that requires a clearance, and darn near anything does now, it will generally turn up.  It may get by a general background check, but eventually (maybe years later) it will come out, your career is over, and you may be charged with fraud.<br>
<br>
Get as much information as possible before signing anything.<br>
